{"id":"quant-ph/0603116","submitter":"Patrick M. Hayden","authors":"Robin Blume-Kohout and Patrick Hayden","title":"Accurate quantum state estimation via \"Keeping the experimentalist\n  honest\"","comments":"5 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  In this article, we derive a unique procedure for quantum state estimation\nfrom a simple, self-evident principle: an experimentalist's estimate of the\nquantum state generated by an apparatus should be constrained by honesty. A\nskeptical observer should subject the estimate to a test that guarantees that a\nself-interested experimentalist will report the true state as accurately as\npossible. We also find a non-asymptotic, operational interpretation of the\nquantum relative entropy function.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 14 Mar 2006 03:16:34 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
